"title": "5618: weights and measures, linear",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5618: weights and measures, linear",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>These terms were based on natural units of measurement that could be easily applied. Measures are given in ascending order, with their approximate imperial and metric equivalents.</p>\n<h2>Finger (1/4 handbreadth): about 3/4 inch (about 1.85 centimetres)</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:21\">JER 52:21</a></strong> <em>The finger was 1/4 handbreadth and was the smallest subdivision of the cubit. This is its only mention in Scripture.</em></p>\n<h2>Handbreadth (4 fingers): about 3 inches (about 8 centimetres)</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:25\">EXO 25:25</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod37:12\">EXO 37:12</a> <em>The handbreadth was the width of the hand at the base of the four fingers.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:5\">PSA 39:5</a> <em>The handbreadth is here used figuratively of the shortness of human life</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:5\">EZK 40:5</a></p>\n<h2>Span (half a cubit): about 9 inches (about 23 centimetres)</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:16\">EXO 28:16</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:9\">EXO 39:9</a> <em>The span was the width of the outstretched hand from thumb to little finger.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:4\">1SA 17:4</a> <em>Goliath's height is given in the Hebrew as “six cubits and a span”</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps90:10\">PSA 90:10</a> <em>The span is here used figuratively of the shortness of human life</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek43:13\">EZK 43:13</a></p>\n<h2>Cubit (2 spans): about 18 inches (about 0.5 metre)</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:10\">EXO 25:10</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod37:1\">EXO 37:1</a> <em>The cubit was the distance from the fingertip to the elbow, and was used to measure height, size, depth and distance.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:20\">GEN 7:20</a> <em>The Hebrew describes the depth of the water as “fifteen cubits”</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:9-Exod27:18\">EXO 27:9–27:18</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:9-Exod38:15\">EXO 38:9–38:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs6:2-1Kgs6:3\">1KI 6:2–6:3</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr3:3-2Chr3:4\">2CH 3:3–3:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr11:23\">1CH 11:23</a> <em>The Hebrew describes the man as “five cubits tall”</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:5\">EZK 40:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:1-Ezek45:6\">EZK 45:1–45:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek47:3-Ezek47:5\">EZK 47:3–47:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John21:8\">JHN 21:8</a> <em>The Greek text describes the distance as “about two hundred cubits”</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:17\">REV 21:17</a></p>\n<h2>Reed (6 cubits): about 10 feet (about 3 metres)</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek41:8\">EZK 41:8</a></strong> <em>Originally a measuring instrument, the reed became a recognised measure of six cubits (the rod).</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:3\">EZK 40:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:5-Ezek40:7\">EZK 40:5–40:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev11:1\">REV 11:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:15-Rev21:16\">REV 21:15–21:16</a></p>\n<h2>Mile</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:41\">MAT 5:41</a></strong> <em>The Greek word for “mile” here is “milion”, a transliteration of the Roman measurement “mille passuum”, “a thousand paces”.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke24:13\">LUK 24:13</a> <em>The measurement in the Greek is “sixty stadia”. Eight stadia were about one mile (about 1480 metres)</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John6:19\">JHN 6:19</a> <em>The measurement in the Greek is “twenty-five or thirty stadia”</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John11:18\">JHN 11:18</a> <em>The measurement in the Greek is “fifteen stadia”.</em></p>",
